<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-589-674  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 589 674.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDGE on andamp; about ATandamp;T  March 19, 1990 v5 n86 p7(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EDGE Publishing 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>US Sprint: joins in building Asia-Pacific (ASPAC) cable system.andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   US Sprint Communications Co. (planning).andO;Topic:     Fiber OpticsInternational CommunicationsStrategic PlanningAsiaPacific Rim CountriesTelephone Companies.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>US SPRINT: JOINS IN BUILDING ASIA-PACIFIC (ASPAC) CABLE SYSTEM US Sprint isparticipating in planning for the construction of an Asian fiber-optic cablesystem to serve the major markets of the Pacific Basin.andM;The 4,500-mile-long Asia-Pacific Submarine Cable (ASPAC), linking Japan,China, Hong Kong and Singapore, will interconnect with several transpacificcable systems serving the United States and Canada.andM;The ASPAC agreement calls for a 560 Mbps link between Tokyo, Shanghai, HongKong and Singapore The cable will be able to handle 30,000 simultaneoustelephone calls.andM;The principal parties in the estimated $260 million project are InternationalDigital Communications (IDC) of Japan, the Telecommunications Authority ofSingapore, Cable andamp; Wireless (Hong Kong) Ltd., and Mercury CommunicationsLtd., of the United Kingdom.andM;US Sprint is participating as the initial U.S.andP;  party for planning of thesystem, which will provide an important supplement to the HongKong-Japan-Korea (H-J-K) Submarine System planned to begin operations inmid-1990.andM;Completion of ASPAC's construction is expected by mid-1993.andP;  US Sprint andother international carriers will purchase capacity on the system as part ofa consortium to be formed later this year.andM;&quot;ASPAC will further extend the reach of the US Sprint fiber-optic networkinto the fast growing Asia-Pacific region,&quot; said Paolo Guidi, president ofSprint International, the private networks and internationaltelecommunications subsidiary of US Sprint.andM;&quot;With the link to the People's Republic of China, it will bring US Sprint'sgoal of a global fiber-optic network one step closer to reality.&quot;andM;US Sprint co-owns the PTAT-1 transatlantic fiber-optic cable with Cable andamp;Wireless and also owns and operates the largest all-fiber network in thecontinental United States.andM;&quot;ASPAC will provide much needed capacity in the Pacific Basin,&quot; said BillBurgess, Sprint International vice president for telecommunications services.andO;&quot;Because the H-J-K cable is forecast to be filled to capacity by 1994, theASPAC cable will be ready just in time to meet the increasing demand forvoice, data and video services in the region.&quot;andO;</TEXT></DOC>